        "$:/language/Help/server": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/server",
            "description": "Provides an HTTP server interface to TiddlyWiki",
            "text": "The server built in to TiddlyWiki5 is very simple. Although compatible with TiddlyWeb it doesn't support many of the features needed for robust Internet-facing usage.\n\nAt the root, it serves a rendering of a specified tiddler. Away from the root, it serves individual tiddlers encoded in JSON, and supports the basic HTTP operations for `GET`, `PUT` and `DELETE`.\n\n```\n--server <port> <roottiddler> <rendertype> <servetype> <username> <password> <host> <pathprefix>\n```\n\nThe parameters are:\n\n* ''port'' - port number to serve from (defaults to \"8080\")\n* ''roottiddler'' - the tiddler to serve at the root (defaults to \"$:/core/save/all\")\n* ''rendertype'' - the content type to which the root tiddler should be rendered (defaults to \"text/plain\")\n* ''servetype'' - the content type with which the root tiddler should be served (defaults to \"text/html\")\n* ''username'' - the default username for signing edits\n* ''password'' - optional password for basic authentication\n* ''host'' - optional hostname to serve from (defaults to \"127.0.0.1\" aka \"localhost\")\n* ''pathprefix'' - optional prefix for paths\n\nIf the password parameter is specified then the browser will prompt the user for the username and password. Note that the password is transmitted in plain text so this implementation isn't suitable for general use.\n\nFor example:\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n\nThe username and password can be specified as empty strings if you need to set the hostname or pathprefix and don't want to require a password:\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html \"\" \"\" 192.168.0.245\n```\n\nTo run multiple TiddlyWiki servers at the same time you'll need to put each one on a different port.\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/setfield": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/setfield",
            "description": "Prepares external tiddlers for use",
            "text": "//Note that this command is experimental and may change or be replaced before being finalised//\n\nSets the specified field of a group of tiddlers to the result of wikifying a template tiddler with the `currentTiddler` variable set to the tiddler.\n\n```\n--setfield <filter> <fieldname> <templatetitle> <rendertype>\n```\n\nThe parameters are:\n\n* ''filter'' - filter identifying the tiddlers to be affected\n* ''fieldname'' - the field to modify (defaults to \"text\")\n* ''templatetitle'' - the tiddler to wikify into the specified field. If blank or missing then the specified field is deleted\n* ''rendertype'' - the text type to render (defaults to \"text/plain\"; \"text/html\" can be used to include HTML tags)\n"

      // backslash\n\t\t.replace(/\"/g, '\\\\\"')              // double quote character\n\t\t.replace(/'/g, \"\\\\'\")              // single quote character\n\t\t.replace(/\\r/g, '\\\\r') !ENG 2118
*[[Syllabus|ENG2118 Syllabus]]
*[[Lectures|ENG2118 Lectures]]
*[[Blackboard Site|https://uottawa.blackboard.com/webapps/blackboard/execute/modulepage/view?course_id=_44015_1&cmp_tab_id=_75408_1&mode=view]]
*[[Study Guide|ENG2118 Study Guide]]







;[[Culture]] 
:A dynamic and ongoing process of producing shared meanings and practices.
;[[Geography]] 
:Dynamic context in which groups shape meaning & use place and space to shape meaning.

''Geography and Culture''

*Geography is interested in ways place and space shape culture, and
*how culture culture shapes place and space
Implicates the
*tangible qualities of place
*intangible qualities of place - symbolic, spiritual (ie, ideas, music)

What role does place or ideas about place play in shaping culture? 
Example: elements of place in ideas about cultural “authenticity” or spatial (racial) segregation 

Video: "Do the Right Thing" Movie Clip: Boycott Sal's

Italian Pizzeria owner vs. black customers:
Black customer wants to see he shape shaped by the culture it inhabits.
 It is decorated as an italian environment, there is no representation of the people who come in there. Prof:  "We want to see our culture shape this place more directly." An example of dual relationship of place and space affecting each other.

"What constitutes authenticity? Is starbucks an authentic coffee shop? We go to the realm of ideas to support our response. Shared meanings and idea shape our ideas about a space."






Culture is never any __//thing.//__ It is a struggled-over set of social relations, intersects with social, political, economic, historical processes.

;Culture
:shared set of meanings that are lived through the material & symbolic practices of everyday life.
Includes: values, beliefs, practices, and ideas about religion, language, family, gender, sexuality, other important identities, architecture, art, music...

>"lived through [...] everyday life."

It is inherently @@.highlight dynamic.@@ They change and evolve.

Examples:

*(in the text) Evolution of traditional French folk music in North America. 
*Tattooing.
*Mechanization in agriculture: changed the nature of labour, in turn changing the culture.

Referenced

*[[Introduction to Cultural Geography]]






(Discussed in text pp. 162-63)

Origins: artists like funkster George Clinton 

Early hip-hop had very ''territorial'' dimensions, claiming space (esp. Public Space).
In the ''Bronx, NYC'': gangs decided to turn from violence and towards creativity (Zulu Nation)

Video: history of hip-hop culture summed up in 10 minutes

A music that existed in the streets, in public space, collaborative.'' [[Public space]] is integral to this cultural expression. ''Literally bringing speakers and turntables into the streets.

Eventually, rapping emerged (original MC'ing). Announcers began to embellish to sentences, paragraphed, verses, rhymes.

An outcome of [[racial segregation]], bringing artists closely together in space to improvice, inovate, collaborate. Tight social relationships.

*West African storytelling  => griot

*Critiques of rap and gangsta rap more specifically
@@.highlight Note the textbook@@

* Counter interpretation of cultural critic bell hooks (understand her argument)

Separates comics from ‘comic art’ : @@.highlight single panels are not comics,@@ just like film stills are not films.






;Gutter 
:Inter-panel space or border is the ‘sine-non-qua’ of McCloud’s definition of comics. “The limbo…[where] human imagination takes two separate images and transforms them into a single idea.”

;Tier 
:A single row of panels.

;Splash 
:A full-page panel, often used as an ‘establishing shot’ that provides sense of setting.

;Spread 
:An image covering more than a single page. Two-page spreads are common. note: larger images read more as a stand-alone piece of art, and slow down the reading pace.

;Bleeds 
:The art is un-bordered, and extends to end of page. Usually occurs on covers, sometimes elsewhere. McCloud calls this “timeless space.”







McCloud: 
@@.highlight
“amplification through simplification.” 
@@

Abstraction can be used to both assist identification with and to objectify/other a character (universalizing and un-individualizing). Abstraction is what enables the hybridity of words and visuals to become comics. (Understanding Comics, pg 92)

;Cartooning 
: A style using line-work to produce iconic characters with varying levels of abstraction. Not all cartoons are comics, and not all comics are cartoons

;Iconic and Non-Iconic Abstraction 
:Representational vs. non-representational.







Origins in Britain, not US.

Draws some inspiration from social geography & concerns around poverty, gender inequality, racial segregation, impact of deindustrailization and countless rounds of economic growth and recession.

Also inspired by cultural studies (multicultural, political engagement) 


Engaged with big questions of the day.


There is an emphasis on the need for geography to investigate: 
 @@.highlight The structure of experience in a changing world @@

Investigates “maps of meaning” : how space and place are central to cultural experience.

Example: Gay men in gay village in Montreal: ability to express identity and culture - place is integral to expression of cultural identity in a larger environment that is hostile.


Very interested (not exclusively) in the Local: study of life in all its plurality.
Landscape studies : heavily critiqued as component of traditional cultural geography 

New cultural geography: more interest in interpretation of the symbolic aspects of landscape -- what identities can be expressed in particular places and why?

Strong emphasis on ideology 

Emphasis on relationship between culture and landscape as outcome of class, gender, race, ethnicity, and eventually sexuality.

Social contestation strong focal point of the work

Identity seen as always being a spatial social practice • What environments particular identities can be expressed in and why








McCloud defines six kinds of panel-to-panel transitions. These are not mutually-exclusive, there is overlap, as there are with [[Word-Image Combinations]].

McCloud also references the effect of the form of the panels themselves on a reader's understanding of the narrative, calling them @@.highlight "panel-shaped blocks of time." @@In comics, "space and time are the same." (think: large and small/ long and short describe the temporal and spatial) the size and shape of panels affect the readers perception of time.


;Moment-to moment 
:Requires little construction by the reader between panels.

;Action-to-action 
:Shows a single subject moving over a progression of actions

;Subject-to-subject 
:Stays within a scene or idea, but moves from one part to another (such as character-to-character in a conversation). Requires more reader participation.

;Scene-to-scene 
:Requires even more reader participation, covering large amount of time and/or space.

;Aspect-to-aspect 
:‘Casting an eye over the scene,’ each focusing on a different aspect. Sometimes reflects a mood rather than a place.

;Non-sequitur 
:Uncommon, no identifiable relationship between panels, or do not initially appear to. (Is it possible for any sequence of panels to be totally unrelated? Our minds try to make connections anyway.)













in 19th c. middle class women "placed" in private sphere

Locations are more than places on a map, or metaphors: they have real material consequences.






*How economic, social, political relations build the characteristics of a place through time
*Social is emphasized, as is the notion of a construction (something that is dynamic). (example of the bronx in lecture 7 recording).

*Place as result of layering of activities that make and remake it

*Interactions between: 

**Webs of economic, social and political relations 
**Individuals positioned with respect to broad relations that occur in and through a particular place













!Culture and Racial Segregation
A spacial expression of cultural difference and oppression, the reciprocal relationship between culture and space.
@@.highlight When cultural ideology reaches material expression in the environment, it reinforces itself, normalizing inequities.@@






Date: January 26, 2016


















@@.highlight
“Space does for comics what time does for film.” 
@@ 
(McCloud)

Space suggests time. Narrative actions are //encapsulated//, providing closure on each panel and linking sequenced panels as encapsulated actions. 






According to C.S. Peirce, 
@@.highlight
signs are a stimulus pattern that conveys meaning.
@@
The difference between signs is how meaning is attached to the stimulus. Three types are defined.

;Icon
:The most simple. Physically resembles what it stands for. Example: onomatopoeia/sound effects in comics.

;Index 
:Defined by some sensory feature (A) directly visible, audible, etc; that correlates with or points to (B) something of interest to an animal. Examples: smoke ⇒ fire, in language when pointing to something present, “I” ⇒ person speaking.

;Symbol 
:A sign which is more abstract, capacious, and easily removable from context. Closely associated with large sets of other words. Most linguistic signs are symbolic (nouns). Example: “the cat” ⇒ a cat that is present is an index, but “cat” ⇒ abstract symbol (think of plato’s realm of forms)

;Synaesthesia 
:Invoking a sense other than the one directly experienced.

;Motion Lines 
:Streaking, comic shorthand for speed, suggests rapid movement within a panel.

;Expressive Lines 
:As a visual medium, comic artists rely on the expressivity of lines to render non-visible phenomenon. 













*Associated with geographer Carl Sauer (1889-1975) - the “Berkeley School” 
*Focus on how a culture expresses itself in the “cultural landscape” 
**Complex interactions between human group & a natural environment

(Diagram in Textbook of his general approach.)
Factors create a natural landscape. People arrive and transform that landscape to meet their needs through culture: a cultural landscape, reshaping nature to fit their needs, creating certain cultural forms.


Example: how the forms of barns reflect certain cultures, distribution of Barn forms across landscape.

Emphasis is on interaction between Human and natural environment.

Comes under critique in 1980s: James Duncan and  the “Superorganic” critique of cultural geography. 
Argues that superorganicism wrongly //reified // culture as a THING rather than as a PROCESS. Problematic because culture defined as a larger-than-life force called "culture," making it impossible to look at the sociological, psychological interpretation of culture, no room for individual, rather automatons that act certain ways because of "culture." Duncan proposes a more sociological definition of culture

Idea of culture as an artifact, and that it can be studied through artifacts.

Sauer was interested in the rural, and ignored urban environments and events (race riots, rights for woman, cultural changes).

Gives rise to [[New Cultural Geography]].







McCloud defines seven kinds of word-image relations.

;Word Specific 
:Pictures serve to illustrate.
;Picture Specific 
:Words “add a soundtrack.’
;Duo-Specific 
:Both provide the same information.
;Additive 
:Words “amplify or elaborate.”
;Parallel 
:Words and pictures don’t intersect.
;Montage 
:Words are part of the picture.
;Interdependent 
:Together, words and pictures convey an idea. There is a variable balance between words and pictures.
